Field Notes - Small beetle (c. 2 mm) outside my glass door in the backyard.

Same species attracted to night light that I posted on iNat about a week ago or more.
This is only the 2nd  one I've seen.Same location near back of dunes.Very loud strong flier.The knobbly  antennae are a characteristic from  my local perspective because I 've been fascinated by our local longhorn beetles(most of which seem to be borers in Acacia trees and shrubs, as far as I can say from my very amateur collecting years in childhood and low teens).We also found the best way to obtain adults diurnally was by stripping the blackish resinous loose bark from the bases of the Acacia uncifolia trees along the rear of Normanville Dunes.But not this species.My guess is it is not a recent arrival e.g. via range extension due climate change.I suspect it is a longterm local native which was probably common pre settlement but became scarce following vegetation clearance and all the other dreadful impacts our forebears had(mostly in ignorancce of consequences) and is making something of a comeback as a result of revegetation and improved landcare generally.All speculation.

description: Acrocinus longimanus (family Cerambycidae) that came to my UV light and moth sheet on the third floor of the Otongachi Reserve Station, La union de Toachi, Santo Domingo de los Tsáchilas Province, Ecuador, about 800 meters elevation.  I let it crawl onto my hand and up onto my shoulders and head as I searched my moth sheet and a mercury-vapor lighted sheet for small keepers.  I let it crawl off onto the other moth sheet from which it eventually flew off un-noticed.  I don't usually collect such large, well-known beetles since the museum already has plenty and because they present a storage and preservation challenge to me.  I normally carry only vials and bottles in three sizes way too small for such giants.

Leaf beetle on eucalypt
? Paropsis sp.
Matrtin Lagerwey:
This beetle is very, very close to P. variicollis including range, larval form and dissection of genitalia, which is a benchmark for ID, however, another name, Paropsisterna cloelia exists and there has been no clarification or synonymy in any published work as yet.

Leaf beetle on eucalypt
? Paropsis sp.
From Martin Lagerwey:
This is possibly the most common paropsine. Roughly speaking, Paropsisterna are a little smaller, have elytral puncturations aligned in ten rows and smooth pronotal edges. Paropsis has puncturaton randomly positioned and pronotal edge crenulate. There are other differences. This species possibly mimics Paropsis porosa, or vice versa. That can get tricky.

The six legs place this beetle in the Arthropoda taxon.
https://bugguide.net/node/view/397
These ladybugs are generally found in developed environments and range across North America and Asia.

description:
So, like @sambiology likes to do, I’m posting an observation in honor of this amazing little gal/fellow.

I was outside this afternoon, working in the yard. I came in later and made a phone call at my desk. I felt something on the back of my neck and gingerly touched my fingers there (I didn’t want to squash anything, might be a spider, you know). Then I found this tiny ant on my arm. I blew on it, thinking it’d fall off on the floor or something. Did it go up my sleeve? I didn’t know, and I promptly forgot about it.

Later I ate supper in the dining roomand then took a hot bath. In the water, I spotted MY ANT! It was VERY submerged. It took me a bit of time to rescue my waterlogged friend. Finally, I drained off the water in my hand and carefully put it on the bathroom counter. It appeared VERY DEAD. But I had hopes. After all, I’ve witnessed ironclad beetles return to life after a day or more of submersion in water.

Well, I forgot about my ant in the bathroom until just a bit ago. I walked back in and carefully put it in my hand....no, it was definitely dead.....

 But WAIT! A leg moved! IT WAS ALIVE! Then an antennae twitched. This called for an iNaturalist observation!

Afterward, I put my little friend on a leaf of my airplane plant in our bedroom. I am just awestruck! Isn’t that so cool?

End of story.

Mentor Marsh State Nature Preserve’s Wake Tobin Boardwalk,
60 F and sunny

At uv.The ants are either attracted to UV OR the very large number of other insets that congregate there. The ants seem to have preferences about the insects they attack and take away. It seems to me that they favour small wasps and bees and seem to really make an effort to attack this particular braconid species.https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/20146751 They completely ignore aphodiinae beetles, most heteroptera, most moths, some leafhoppers but go crazy if they come across https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/20146751 .The wasps are dismembered and the parts carried down to their nest.Since there are so many insects present perhaps the ants can afford to be very choosy and have preferences.

This organism is about 1 cm. in length and a third of a centimeter in width. The genus, Anomala, shiny leaf chafers, has as many as 1,200 species on record. This species in particular appears shiny and gold with a dark brown, almost black, head and strip along the beetle’s back. Commonly, beetles within this genus feed on grass roots. Anomala are present across continents but are most prevalent in south-east United States, around Europe, southern Africa, and in a multitude of countries in Asia. The observation was taken on February 8, 2019 at the University of South Florida. The weather was clear skies on a sunny afternoon with a temperature of 80 degrees Fahrenheit. The taxonomy is as follows: Kingdom Animalia, Phylum Arthropoda, Subphylum Hexapoda, Class Insecta, Order Coleoptera, Family Scarabaeidae, and Genus Anomala. The species of this specific individual is unknown to the observer. For more information: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/92957-Anomala

This rice beetle was seen on the screen of a porch in a backyard in Lakeland, Florida. The habitat it was found in was an urban habitat. It was around 9PM, so it was dark out and the temperature was in the mid 70s. It is found throughout southeastern United States and some western states. They can be found in just about any habitat, including hot, dry, moist, or cold. This insect was about 1/2 inch in length and was black in color with a shine to its body. These beetles are commonly found in Florida, and it was evident that it was a rice beetle due to its body shape being oblong, black in color with a shiny coating, and front claws. They are in the Kingdom Animalia. In more detail, they are in the Superphylum Ecdysozoans under the Protostomes, in the Phylum Arthropoda, within the Hexapods. This organism is indeed an insect because of the fact it has 6 legs, wings, and 3 distinct body parts.

http://entnemdept.ufl.edu/creatures/misc/beetles/rice_beetle.htm

description:
This organism was found in a shaded area on a leaf at lettuce lake park. It was approximately 80°F and humid outside. The bug was about an inch long in length and oval in shape; the head was narrower than the rear. Its base body color was yellow and two black stripes were present on its body. Both were about the same width all the way through, however the middle one was thinner in width and the larger one towards its rear thicker. Attached to the body were two spindly black legs and two black antennae. 
Based on location and appearance, this organism is Calopteran discrepans or Calopteran reticulatum; but more likely to be the discrepans type. These two species are similar in appearance, but the discrepans type differs from the reticulatum in that the stripes tend to be uniform in width. Discrepans limbs and antennae tend to be black whereas reticulatum tend to be rust colored.
These bugs are typically found around in Mexico or eastern north America in states such as Minnesota, Florida, Texas, and South Dakota.

Kingdom Animalia, Phylum Arthropoda, Subphylum Hexapoda, Class Insecta, Order, Coleoptera, Family Lycidae

some tiger beetles with hairy metallic reddish heads and thorax and less hairy reddish back with white markings. i first noticed a pair that was mating, and then a single individual came along and started digging around. the larger (female) beetle in the mating pair also started digging. i thought the digging was to make a nest, but none of the beetles dug deep enough to make a burrow. so maybe they were just looking for something in the sand. these beetles seemed to be more common and slightly larger than the other tiger beetles today on the bank of the bayou. they were easily startled, though they didn't fly far away and tended to return quickly.

This is deliberately an observation of multiple cicada species ... a little story : My gumboots sit outside the back door, and are maybe used once a week. Like the cowboys in the movies I always shake them out before putting them on, not with the expectation of finding scorpions, but expectation to find any manner of other arthropods (spiders, weta, moths, huhu beetles). I tipped up one, and a cicada fell out, I mumbled some speculation about why it went in there, I tipped up the other and there was a clatter as about 17 cicada fell out! These photos were taken some time later, so only show a selection that hadn't been walked on. So I don't know why, maybe black rubber boots retain the sun's warmth and are attractive shelters ???

I went back this afternoon, despite howling winds and 100% overcast skies, because it was ~ 20 deg. F warmer, with fingers crossed for better luck.  Almost nothing was moving besides Eleodes, so I was mostly looking for larval burrows and flipping rocks.  Much to my astonishment, I eventually found this guy, dead and desiccated, just sitting in the middle of a tiny wash, about 35m "downstream" from last Saturday's. It used to be called Didymocantha quadriguttata Sharp, 1886. Biostatus:

The species is endemic to NZ, and apparently is quite widespread.

The specimen has been pinned and now resides in the AsureQuality insect collection, lab Ref: 74156.
